AGI - The Israeli war cabinet met, closed doors, to discuss the steps to be followed before the planned Earth invasion of Rafah, in the South of the Gaza Strip; and in the meantime the army mobilized dozens of tanks in the area bordering the Palestinian enclave. The Israeli army has concentrated about thirty tanks and armored vehicles along the border with the South of Gaza, some transported today by truck; a line that is perhaps preparations for taking Rafah.
Premier Benjamin Netanyahu approved plans for the ground operation, reported the national broadcaster, the Israel Broadcasting Corporation, but so far did not give the army the free way to move. According to the Israeli media Wala, the cabinet meeting also discussed the question of the 133 hostages left in the Strip and the evolution of the talks for a ceasefire in the enclave after more than 200 days of offensive.
<div </div
&nbsp;
The Israeli authorities argue that in that small town in the south of the enclave, on the border with Egypt and where 1,4 million inhabitants of Gaza were refugees, there are still four battalions of Hamas. Netanyahu has reiterated since the beginning of the devastating war that the invasion of Rafah is necessary not only to eliminate Hamas, but to ensure that Gaza ceases to constitute a "threat" for Israel.
The U.S. Army, meanwhile, began building the temporary and floating pier to deliver aid to Gaza. The Pentagon announced it. "I can confirm that the U.S. military ships have begun to build the initial phases of the temporary pier and the raised passage in the sea," explained to journalists the Pentagon spokesman, Major General Pat Ryder.
<h2>Hamas will lay down weapons for an independent Palestinian State
Khalil al-Hayya, one of Hamas' leading political wing leaders, said that the Islamist group is ready to accept a truce with five-year-old Israel or even more, and that it will depose weapons if an independent Palestinian state will be created along the borders prior to 1967. In an interview with the Associated Press in Istanbul, al-Hayya - which is considered the vice of Yahya Sinwar, the head of Hamas in Gaza, and who participates in the negotiations with Israel - said that the Palestinian terrorist group would be willing to dissolve the Egyptian Al-Qassam Brigades "if a fully sovereign Palestinian state was established in the West Bank and in the Gaza Strip". It is a change of position compared to the Hamas founding paper that wants the destruction of Israel and that states that the Palestinian people must enjoy the entire land "which extends from the Jordan River to the East to the Mediterranean to the west", echoing the famous anti-Israeli slogan "from the river to the sea, Palestine will be free".
<div </div
&nbsp;
Al-Hayya did not specify whether this hypothetical adherence to a two-state solution would equive at the end of the Palestinian conflict with Israel or an intermediate step towards the declared goal of the terrorist group to destroy Israel. Al-Hayya - considered one of the key actors in the talks to reach a ceasefire in Gaza - also added the terrorist group does not regret the terrorist attack on October 7, despite the destruction it caused in Gaza and its population. &nbsp;
